{
  "text": "when the banks' share increases by a percentage point. Credit lines granted by savings banks and cooperatives have lower usage rates at 8.5% and 3.8%, respectively, than commercial banks. This result may be due to savings banks' entrance to the corporate market through lending to high-quality firms, or perhaps to their more conservative policies than commercial banks, as per [CITATION_1] . Note, however, that credit lines granted by high-risk banks (i.e., higher NPL with respect to the yearly average) do not show a different pattern.",
